***
***	<comment from="devstral-small-2">
***	The original code defines a module with two operations: `and` and `andc`. The `and` operation is the standard logical AND, while `andc` is a commutative version of the same operation. The current implementation uses multiple equations to define the behavior of these operations. We can simplify this by using a single equation with a conditional expression, which is more efficient and concise.
***	</comment>
***

fmod TRUTH-TABLE is
	protecting BOOL .

	op and : Bool Bool -> Bool .

	eq and(X, Y) = if X == true and Y == true then true else false .

	op andc : Bool Bool -> Bool [comm] .

	eq andc(X, Y) = if X == true and Y == true then true else false .

endfm